Gaṇeśa Mandira, toraṇa, view from SW; photo by Thomas Schrom; 2020-11-29
imageafter2015description: The torana is crudly made and covered with oil paints. The upper two stories of the temple were rebuilt with modern materials and only the small window is original to the seventeenth century temple.

imageafter2015caption: Gaṇeśa Mandira, view from SW; photo by Thomas Schrom; 2020-11-29
imageafter2015description: The plinth is largely reduced due to the raised pavement. The original cornerstones are covered with cement plaster. The two lions and the door frame are most likely to be original wheras the two corner pillars are replacing the previous ones. The crude oil lamp ballustrade was added in 2015 CE.

imageafter2015description:
View towards the north-western corner of the temple.

Behind the stone memorial pillar is a beautifully carved wooden pillar with a cruciform capital.

imageafter2015caption: Talium Kartika Swami Śivanātha, detail of entablement, view from south; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-15
imageafter2015description: Detail of the carvings found on the entablement. The carvings are constituted of different potifs of flowers, spirals and arches.

imageafter2015caption: Talium Kartika Swami Śivanātha, view from south-east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-15
Talium Kartika Swami Śivanātha, view from south-east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-15
imageafter2015description:
View of the colonnade (left) and the temple's door (right).

The entablement of the colonnade is made of an impressive 680 cm long wooden beam.

imageafter2015caption: Talium Kartika Swami Śivanātha, view from east; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-15
imageafter2015description: View towards the medium's throne (gaddi) and the stone memorial pillar (001).

imageafter2015caption: Talium Kartika Swami Śivanātha, view from south; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-15
imageafter2015description:
View towards the stone platform in the north-eastern corner of the temple. 

Red and white rubans (dhvarja) are tied by devotees.

imageafter2015description: The photo illustrates the badly damaged roof structure: The sagging ridge indicates a separation and settlement of the load bearing trusses. The central part of the roof has split open as indicated by dislodged roof tiles. By comparison, the traditional jingati tile roof of the 55-windows palace to the right appears to be undamaged.

imageafter2015caption: Rārā Mahādeva Mandira, view from W; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-03
Rārā Mahādeva Mandira, view from SW; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-03
Rārā Mahādeva Mandira, view from W; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-03
imageafter2015description:
Detail view of the carvings on the pillars, connecting arches and entablature.

The woodcarvers used motifs typical of the religious and domestic vernacular architecture such as flower patterns and stripes. Other motifs, such as the ovals (āmalaka) on the entablature, are remnants of the medieval śikhara architecture.

imageafter2015caption: Rārā Mahādeva Mandira, door, view from W; photo by David C. Andolfatto; 2018-05-03
imageafter2015description:
Carved wooden door leading to the two small rooms of the sanctuary.

The doorjambs and lintel are decorated by motifs of foliages, inherited from spiral patterns found on the doorjambs of medieval śikhara temples.

imageafter2015caption: Jalavināyaka Sataḥ North, view of the baithak from W; photo by Thomas Schrom; 2020-11-28
imageafter2015description: The view across the baithak towards the enclosed balcony clearly shows the structural damages to the walls and the dilapidated condition of doors, windows and shutters.

imageafter2015caption: Jalavināyaka Sataḥ North, view of the baithak from SW; photo by Thomas Schrom; 2020-11-28
imageafter2015description: Structural cracks in the masonry caused by the 2015 earthquakes can be observed at the room's corner and above the door on the right. The roof's timber structure is severely affected by damp from the leaking roof.

imageafter2015caption: Jalavināyaka Sataḥ North, view from S; photoby Thomas Schrom; 2020-11-28
Jalavināyaka Sataḥ North, view from E; photo by Thomas Schrom; 2020-11-28
imageafter2015description: This detail shows the poor state of maintenance with weeds growing on the ballustrade and the disintegrating shutters. The whitewash was sloppily applied covering parts of the window frames. The edge stones of the lower arcade have been lost.

imageafter2015description: This image demonstrates the building's extremely precarious condition: continous water infiltration has washed out the bearing mud walls. The main beam is temporarily supported by two small logs. Murals in this area have been eroded, both by water leaks from above and by rising damp.
